VALUES
(41, 14, 54, 40, 26, 3, 3, 'palace of the high priest', 'Peter''s Presence at Caiaphas'' Palace', 'This connection highlights Peter''s physical proximity to the high priest''s palace, where the chief priests and elders convened. Both passages emphasize the significance of the high priest''s location in the unfolding events surrounding Jesus'' trial.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 54, 43, 18, 25, 25, 'warmed himself at the fire', 'Peter''s Denial and Fire', 'Both passages emphasize Peter warming himself at the fire while denying his association with Jesus. This connection highlights the moment of Peter''s denial occurring in a similar setting, illustrating his fear and separation from Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 54, 9, 13, 7, 7, 'followed him afar off', 'Following from Afar', 'This connection highlights the theme of following from a distance in both passages. Peter''s act of following Jesus ''afar off'' parallels the trembling Hebrews who followed Saul, suggesting a sense of fear and uncertainty in their loyalty.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 54, 11, 19, 9, 9, 'sat with the servants, and warmed himself', 'Isolation and Seeking God', 'This connection highlights the theme of isolation in both passages. Peter''s distancing from Jesus at the fire parallels Elijah''s retreat to the cave, where he seeks God''s presence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 54, 40, 26, 58, 58, 'Peter followed him afar off', 'Peter''s Follow and Observation', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s action of following Jesus from a distance and sitting with the servants. This connection highlights Peter''s desire to witness the unfolding events surrounding Jesus'' trial.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 54, 41, 14, 29, 31, 'followed him afar off', 'Peter''s Denial and Following', 'This connection highlights Peter''s commitment to follow Jesus despite his eventual denial. In Mark 14:54, Peter''s action of following ''afar off'' contrasts with his earlier declaration of unwavering loyalty in Mark 14:29-31.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 55, 40, 5, 22, 22, NULL, 'Judgment and Council Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and the role of the council in both passages. In Mark, the council seeks witnesses to condemn Jesus, while in Matthew, being judged by the council is linked to anger and insults among brothers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 55, 40, 26, 59, 60, 'found none', 'Connection of False Witnesses', 'Both passages emphasize the search for witnesses against Jesus. Mark notes that they ''found none,'' while Matthew elaborates that many false witnesses came but still found none initially.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 55, 44, 24, 1, 13, 'found none', 'Accusation and Judicial Proceedings', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of false accusations against key figures, with Mark highlighting the lack of witnesses against Jesus and Acts detailing the unfounded charges against Paul. This connection highlights the continuity of judicial injustices faced by early followers of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 55, 60, 3, 16, 18, NULL, 'Suffering for Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for doing good. In Mark, Jesus is falsely accused, while 1 Peter discusses suffering for well doing, emphasizing the unjust treatment of the righteous.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 55, 11, 21, 13, 13, 'witness against Jesus', 'False Witness and Injustice', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of false witnesses seeking to condemn the innocent. In Mark, the chief priests sought witnesses against Jesus, while in 1 Kings, men of Belial falsely accused Naboth to secure his death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 55, 19, 27, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of False Witnesses', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of false witnesses against the innocent. Mark 14:55 mentions the search for witnesses against Jesus, while Psalms 27:12 speaks of false witnesses rising up against the psalmist.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 55, 19, 35, 11, 11, 'witness against Jesus', 'False Witnesses Against Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of false witnesses arising against the innocent. Both passages emphasize the unjust accusations faced by the righteous, with Mark noting the search for witnesses against Jesus and Psalms mentioning false witnesses laying charges.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 57, 40, 26, 60, 61, 'bare false witness against him', 'False Witnesses in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of false witnesses during the trial of Jesus. Mark 14:57 mentions those who bore false witness, while Matthew 26:60-61 describes the failure to find credible witnesses until two came forward.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 57, 44, 6, 13, 14, 'bare false witness against him', 'False Witnesses Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bearing false witness against Jesus. In Mark, false witnesses arise to accuse him, while in Acts, false witnesses are set up to claim blasphemy against him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 57, 24, 26, 8, 9, 'bare false witness against him', 'False Witness and Prophecy', 'This connection highlights the theme of false accusations against prophets. Both passages depict individuals bearing false witness, leading to severe consequences for the prophets involved.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 57, 24, 26, 18, 18, 'bare false witness against him', 'False Witness and Prophecy', 'This connection highlights the theme of false testimony against prophetic figures. Both passages emphasize the consequences of speaking against God''s messengers, as seen in the false witnesses in Mark and the prophetic warning in Jeremiah.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 57, 40, 27, 40, 40, 'bare false witness against him', 'False Witness and Mockery', 'This connection highlights the theme of false accusations against Jesus. Both passages reflect the hostility he faced, with Mark noting false witnesses and Matthew depicting mockery regarding his claims.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 57, 41, 15, 29, 29, 'bare false witness against him', 'False Witness and Mockery', 'This connection highlights the theme of false accusations leading to mockery. In both passages, individuals are speaking against Jesus, first through false witness and later through derision as they pass by.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 57, 43, 2, 18, 21, 'bare false witness against him', 'False Witness and Misunderstanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding and false testimony. In Mark, false witnesses arise against Jesus, while in John, the Jews misunderstand His statement about the temple, reflecting a similar theme of misinterpretation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 58, 43, 2, 19, 19, 'I will destroy this temple', 'Connection of Temple Destruction', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of the temple and the promise of its restoration in three days. This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' words regarding the temple''s fate.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 58, 47, 5, 1, 1, 'made without hands', 'Connection of Temples and Buildings', 'This connection highlights the concept of a ''building not made with hands'' in both passages. Mark 14:58 refers to a temple that Jesus will build, while 2 Corinthians 5:1 speaks of an eternal house from God, emphasizing a spiritual reality beyond physical structures.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 58, 58, 9, 11, 11, 'made without hands', 'Connection of Temples and Tabernacles', 'This connection highlights the concept of a ''temple'' or ''tabernacle'' not made with hands. Both passages emphasize the idea of a divine structure that transcends physical buildings.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 58, 41, 15, 29, 29, 'I will destroy this temple', 'Connection of Temple Destruction', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of the temple''s destruction and rebuilding. The first passage presents a claim about destroying the temple, while the second passage references this claim during mockery.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 58, 44, 7, 48, 48, NULL, 'Connection of Temples and Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that God does not dwell in physical structures made by human hands. Mark 14:58 speaks of a temple made with hands, while Acts 7:48 directly states that the Most High does not dwell in such temples.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 58, 58, 9, 24, 24, 'temple that is made with hands', 'Connection Between Temple References', 'This connection highlights the contrast between physical temples and the spiritual reality of Christ''s presence. Both passages emphasize the idea of a temple not made with hands, indicating a shift from the physical to the spiritual.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 58, 27, 2, 34, 34, 'made without hands', 'Connection of Divine Construction', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine creation without human intervention. Both passages emphasize the idea of something being built ''without hands'', suggesting a supernatural act of construction.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 60, 40, 26, 62, 63, 'what is it which these witness against thee?', 'High Priest''s Inquiry to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the high priest''s question to Jesus about the witnesses against him. The phrasing in both accounts is nearly identical, highlighting the moment of interrogation. This connection illustrates the shared narrative of Jesus'' trial.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 60, 41, 15, 3, 5, 'Answerest thou nothing?', 'Silence of Jesus in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' silence in response to accusations. The high priest and Pilate both question him about his lack of defense, highlighting a thematic parallel in the narrative of his trial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 60, 43, 19, 9, 10, 'Answerest thou nothing?', 'Silence Before Accusation', 'This connection highlights the theme of silence in the face of accusation. In both passages, Jesus remains silent when questioned by authority figures, emphasizing his composure amidst unjust treatment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
